## 5. Graphs The following graphs were generated: - Training vs validation loss graph - Training vs validation accuracy graph - Confusion matrix - Class distribution graph These graphs help explain the model performance and dataset balance. 
## 6. GUI Description The PyQt GUI allows the user to load the saved BERT model and the Twitter dataset. After loading the dataset, tweets are displayed inside the application. When the user clicks a tweet, the model predicts its sentiment. The GUI also includes a manual text box where the user can type a new sentence and get the predicted sentiment. 
## 7. Paul's Critical Thinking Standards Clarity: The dataset columns, labels, and GUI workflow were clearly defined. Accuracy: The model was evaluated using actual accuracy, precision, recall, F1-score, and confusion matrix. Precision: The model name, batch size, epochs, learning rate, and train-test split were mentioned. Relevance: Only relevant graphs such as loss, accuracy, confusion matrix, and class distribution were included. Depth: The model may perform differently on slang, short tweets, sarcasm, or unclear sentences. Logic: The workflow follows a proper sequence: dataset cleaning, model training, model saving, model loading, and GUI prediction. Fairness: The dataset may contain bias because Twitter data can include informal language, slang, and class imbalance. A balanced dataset was used to reduce bias. 
## 8. Conclusion The project successfully trained a BERT model for Twitter sentiment analysis and connected it with a PyQt desktop GUI. The final application can load a trained model, load a dataset, predict sentiment from selected tweets, and predict sentiment from manually typed text.
